segments.text: This is July 13, sitting in the study of Raul Fernandez in San Antonio, and delighted to have the opportunity to chat with him about his student days.
I think I mentioned to you the first question I would ask would be, why did you go to A&M in the first place?
Why did you go there instead of somewhere else?
And were you, like me, from a working class background, and going to college was a big step?
It was a big step, no question.
See, both my parents were born in Mexico and neither probably finished grade school.
However, they instilled in us, you're going to go to college.
You're going to go to college.
And I believed that.
And there was no decision for me to make.
I followed my brothers.
And my brother Gus, who was a freshman in 49, and then Albert.
And Gus passed 53, and then Albert passed 54.
And Albert graduated on the night that I graduated from high school.
He graduated from A&M.
And so we just switched places, and he went back to Laredo, and I went to College Station.
And your class of?
And did you visit A&M before?
I had the occasion to go a few times, both on a, I already had my mind made up, but we got a day to go visit a college or university.
And the three of us from Laredo, we drove up there and spent the day at A&M.
There was no other consideration for me.
I applied to one university, and I was very fortunate to have a $250 scholarship, if I remember correctly, from the Laredo A&M Mothers Club.
And God bless them for that, because at that time, it cost $800 to $900 for everything for a year.
And so that was like a 25% supplement to what I was about.
And so I didn't work the first semester.
But it took me, I crammed four into five.
And 10 semesters, I worked nine.
The first one, I didn't have to.
I felt like that was OK.
While you're on that subject of work, what were your work?
At A&M?
Where did you work?
Well, I had, most of the time,
I worked around the MSC.
Mid-semester of my freshman year I got a job in what used to be the MSC reading library down the lower level.
It was like a reading library and then it became something else after that.
I started there and then
about towards the end of my freshman year of the semester, a job opened up making signs in the basement.
I remember the elevator used to go down and you'd open the doors and you'd go into there, there'd be a cage right in front of you, a lot of work in that cage.
And we had an embossed graphing machine there and we made all the signs for the university.
What was your pay, do you remember?
No, but I worked for Herbie Johns.
Mr. Johns was the, I guess he was the manager of the MSC at the time.
Gosh, I don't remember.
Maybe 35, 40 cents an hour.
Maybe, maybe 50 cents.
Now, did you work in the MSC nine semesters?
Yes, all night.
However, other times I had one other job, and one time I had three jobs.
What were those others?
Being an engineering major, I got the opportunity to work at TTI, Texas Transportation Institute, and we did testing of cylinders and the kinds of things we did in a lab.
We learned that, and we'd go over there and do grunt work and
Mike Woodson and Wesley Heald and I, we were all running buddies.
I think Wesley is just the new chief engineer for the highway department, if you heard his name bad around.
So we would work at that.
My brother Gus worked with me three years in making signs, because right after I got there, the brother person was there left, and so I got Gus to come in there, and so we worked together.
How did
When you got, let's go back now to, you're going to enroll as a freshman.
How did you get there on that trip?
When I went to university, a dear friend of mine, Danny Flores, his mother, his mother took Danny and David Loudell and me, and she drove us up there.
I shipped a footlocker and took a little Samsonite suitcase that I'd been given,
Describe what was in those two containers.
What did you take with you?
Not much.
Not much, Haskell.
Towels, sheets, underwear.
We didn't have a whole lot of clothes.
We just didn't in those days.
And enough clothes to escape when you could.
And not a whole lot.

not a typewriter no not a radio uh wasn't a freshman privilege in our call but uh it wasn't it wasn't on the first on the first trip did you i'll call us of it did you take in a civilian suit or dress coat i don't think so do you remember how long the drive took an hour it's a six hour drive okay okay between six and seven hours okay even even the expressways yeah i drive right through san antonio from
Right up all the, up from Broadway and up Nogalitos.
Because San Antonio is almost exactly halfway, isn't it?
Exactly.
Describe how you, where did you get out at and where did you put your stuff?
You know, move me into the dormitory.
Yeah.
The other, let me see.
I was in, I was in,
assigned to B-triple-A.
There was only one, no, there was two core areas at the time.
We just drove up to the core area.
The new core area.
Around Duncan.
Around Duncan, yeah.
Actually, I don't know.
We called the new area dorms 16, 17, and 18.
I was in dorm 17 my freshman year.
And Danny was in the same area.
Regiment, we were 2nd Regiment, and he was in Quartermaster's.
And then Dave was an engineer, so he was over there on Duncan.
We were over there by Sabisa.
Oh, you were by Sabisa?
Yeah.
We had two corps airs there.
Do you remember any sudden realizations that you now were in the corps that first day?
Did anything happen?
Any sophomore pounce on you?
No, I really don't remember that happening.
We got there probably before the sophomores did.
And we kind of had a weekend with the first sergeant and maybe a few other people.
And the sophomores got there Sunday night.
Did you go to fish camp?
No.
No, I did not.
I don't do that any fish camp tonight.
I don't know.
No.
What about registration?
Do you remember that, that first time?
Frankly, no.
I really don't remember.
I remember the registration process.
It was just something you had to do.
You didn't ask.
We just did what we had to do.
Tell me about how you got oriented, broken into, introduced to being a fish.
How did the sophomores?
Frankly, I thought it was a game.
It was, to me, it was a game.
And I wasn't intimidated by the sophomores.
I knew what to expect.
Both my brothers had been in the Corps.
And they couldn't eat me.
And I was in a reasonable outfit.
They were pretty tough, but we were tougher.
And we took great joy in hazing sophomores.
And I think we did a real good job of it.
A lot of people knew my name.
Describe your room, your fish year, physically.
What was in it?
What did it look like?

Okay, we had, you know, you walk in, depending on what side of the, the laboratories were, say if I walk in, the laboratories on the right, we actually had a closet behind the door, and then you had a, of course, the other closet from the other unit, I guess, was there, too.
We had a laboratory.
We had a double metal...
metal bed, bunk bed.
And they each came with a mattress, and I think they came with a pillow too.
And there was two desks at the end.
There was a window at the end with a radiator, one of those steam jobbies.
And the closet was small.
We didn't have much.
And we got more clothes there assigned to us by the department, the military science department.
and then we probably brought up there, I think we must have had at least two or three uniforms issued and fatigues.
Of course, we supplemented that and bought more other uniforms that really had form fit, so you wouldn't look like cadet slouch.
Did you have anything, any decoration on the wall or the floor?
Nothing.
Curtains?
Absolutely not.
And what floor?
Fourth floor.
Tufts, as a freshman, are the best for studying.
Oh, I hadn't thought about that.
But you meet a lot of people.
And you also get very fast going upstairs.
And you can just slip around the end of the metal banisters going up and down, where you just grease out those things.
But you had to meet them anyway, sooner or later.
So you might as well just do it.
And so we got to meet all the freshmen.
And sophomores and seniors, there were the other two.
I was in B-triple-A.
Did it have a nickname?
No, we didn't use nicknames at that time.
We were B-anti-aircraft artillery, and we were proud of it.
And these kids today are proud of what they are, and that's okay.
But A-triple-A and B-triple-A and C-triple-A were the same door.
And the way the selection process went, whichever unit was the top unit in the scoring for general war got their choice of floors.
And if you were the best out there in that battalion, you always took the top floor because it was the quietest, even though you had to go up three flights.
But at that age, and even now, it's not a problem.
Take me, let's make believe we're in the middle of the fall, your fish year.
Take me through a typical class day.
In other words, a Monday through Friday.
What time did you get up and so forth?
Ah.

I know when we got up, we didn't have a whole long time to get ready and hit the quad for formation to mark to breakfast and the whistle jock would run up and down the halls blowing the whistle and saying how long time it was to formation and you'd get a
I'd wake up and then you'd have a warning to the time, to formation.
You'd want your breakfast.
And then we would, if we were really quick, we'd do some of our room before we left or when we got back when you, when you tidied up your room and your, got your, got your things together.
But you had to leave your room straight.
You had to leave it absolutely tip-top.
And a lot of time before we'd go to bed at night, we had everything except maybe wiping down your lab or
clean a mirror or straighten out something that might have, you know, beds were always made.
I can't remember if we made them before we left or probably after because you had to hustle with two people to get out to formation and make sure you had all your grass on.
It took a long time at first, but then after a while, after you got, you knew the game, what they were looking for, it wasn't a problem.
Right, and you all fell in where?
In front of the dorm.
And march to?
March to Sabisa.
Then go back to, after breakfast, go back?
Go back on your own.
And do what?
Well, you finish cleaning up your room.
Most of us had class at 8 o'clock.
Did you ever take care of a sophomore's room also, or a junior's?
No.
You didn't have that?
I did not do that.
All right.
Then noon, did you all fall out and march?
Absolutely.
We'd have a...
Formation, probably 10 to five minutes before the hour, and march to lunch.
And you were at formation.
Everybody was at formation.
Most seniors were at formation, too.
Of course, there wasn't any place else to eat.
You either ate there or at the MSC.
And everybody went.
All right.
Then in the afternoons, what if you had any spare time?
Well, I never had a whole lot of spare time.
maybe that first semester, but that time you're trying to adapt to college life and playing the game.
But we took too many classes, bottom line.
I think we were dumb or we weren't counseled as well as kids are today.
But consequently, you'd end up, you're taking 17, 18 hours and maybe you only pass 14 or 15.
And a lot of us,
A lot of us did that.
I'm not ashamed of it.
But the important thing is to never quit.
I flunked countless, three times before I passed it.
Passed it on the fourth time, but I never quit.
But we always had time to get back.
We had intramurals.
That was part of our company strategy
Everybody participate.
Professional played with freshmen, then upperclassmen had their own deals.
We would march a lot.
Before dinner, we weren't doing intramurals unless somebody had someplace to be.
The unit had things to keep us busy and keep us on task.
Learn how to march was important to this group and important to me.
There was always training going on.
How was supper different in routine if it was to lunch and breakfast?
Had a little more time.
And there was more time for old, trained freshmen.
And it was a sophomore job.
And seniors and juniors would play with us.
You know how that goes.
Describe the task of a typical fish
Well we sat in the middle and you're passing stuff and or in the hot corner.

In the hot corner you got the food from the waiter at that time it was family style and the waiters would come and you'd have to you know grab it off the waiters and pass it around but usually the juniors and seniors sat on the outside fresh on the hot corner and then I think there was eight to the table if I remember correctly it could have been ten and you had at least one or two sophomores at the table and
One or two freshmen.
I understand that some Aggie food had a special Aggie name.
They all had names.
Can you remember as many of those as you can?
Oh, probably.
Bread was gunwadi.
Mustard was baby.
Eggs were cackle, I believe.
Bullmeck, obviously, was meat.
And there were just a lot of...
Beans?
I don't remember what beans were.
Corn?
Ketchup?
Ketchup and blood, yeah.
Let's see, tea, coffee, dessert.
Dessert was a kush.
And all dessert was kush?
All dessert was kush.
It was pie or cake?
Yeah, everything.
And from there came the kush questions.
Did you ever, when you were home, did you ever forget
and asked for something.
I'm sure we all did.
And maybe some of them I did on purpose.
In an Aggie fashion?
Yeah.
Oh, yeah.
Let's see.
All right.
Now, did your freshman year, did you and your classmates ever wait till all the upperclassmen left?
If you wanted to eat.
So you could really eat?
Sure.
But they always left in time to make sure we had enough time to eat.
I mean, they didn't stick around.
They had to go, too.
But I never left the mess hall hungry.
I never, ever left the mess hall hungry.
In general, what was the quality of the food?
I thought it was great.
Frankly, it was good.
Did you have a particular favorite dish, as you think back on it?
I had a real standard stomach, and there may have been some favorite, but it was reasonably good.
Was there any that you all really disliked?
I've not heard of any.
I was just wondering.
I don't even think they ever service .
That's one of the things I'm already fond of.
Everything else is fine.
Define hazing as it was in your day.
What happened in or around the dorms that an investigator today would say, oh, that's hazing?
Nobody ever touched me.
Nobody ever hit me.
Now, we might have been out at a company party or something.
And if you wanted to trade licks with a broom with a sophomore and you felt like that was as close as I would say, never.
Nobody ever beat my ass.
I don't remember.
Not many have said that.
Usually a broomstick or part of a baseball bat.
Nobody.
Absolutely.
Only in fun, like I say, and we pride ourselves on being able to take a lick or give a lick.
But you would trade, and that was okay.
And some of them were popping pretty good.
All right, but push-ups and duck walking, what else?
We didn't run like the court runs today, but I learned hold the wall up.
You heard that game?
Describe it.
Well, where you put your back on the wall and you form a chair-like with your legs, with your
with your thighs being parallel to the floor.
And it really builds up your legs really good.
Sometimes you do it so long, they start to tremble and you fall down.
But it builds a little character, especially if you're trying to get your attention.
I can't recall what all the... Now, would a sophomore direct you to hold the ball up?
Oh, yeah.
So be freshman, give me five.
Would that be push-up?
Five or more, I suspect.
But now the juniors do push-up because they love their class year.
Four guys from 99 are going to have a problem.
But we didn't do that.
So we didn't do push-ups.
And then after a while, we'd just do it ourselves just to build up.
We could compete with sophomores and show them that, hey, I can take it.
And we duck walked.
We duck walked a lot.
Duck walked in your raincoat, in your helmet, liner.
We did that, even the sophomores, when we stole the junior blouses.
And we had a lot of fun with them on that.
Describe that.
Okay.
When we were sophomores, you know, the junior ball comes up, and the custom, the tradition was the sophomores would go over and steal the junior's uniform so that they couldn't go to the ball.
And the game was they would,
torment you and haze you until you say, we give up.
And of course, nobody ever gives up.
Finally, the CO will come and say, all right, guys, give it back to them.
Oh, okay, we don't want to, but we'll do it.

And we had a couple of juniors, we had a couple of gentlemen who were, I remember Dan Greenberg in Houston, he was a vet major, and he wore glasses about that thick of Coke bottles, and he didn't get a contract, but
There was one other, one other, I can't remember who that was.
But anyway, when we said we're gonna, we had a sophomore meeting and we're going to steal the blouses.
And I said, you know, we can't leave Dan Greenberg out.
I mean, he's part of this group.
And so we, and there was one other.
So anyway, we said the mission.
I think I went to Greenberg's room and his roommate was there.
And I said, Dan said for me to come up and pick up a suit.
He wanted me to take it to the cleaners.
Grab her suit.
It's the funniest thing.
We were the first meeting that they called the sophomores in.
And they're sitting on the beds, and we're sitting on the floor like freshmen again with our knees under our chins.
And bang, the door just busts open.
And damn Greenberg walks in, says, where's that damn bully Fernandez?
He stole my suit.
Sir.
Anyway, so yeah.
You learn a lot of things in that.
There was an incident, and I probably won't touch on that, that happened that sophomores learn, even at that stage, juniors rather, even at that stage, you've got to watch what you say.
And that's the place to learn, to make a mistake, not after your professional life or other things.
But it isn't fun.
You're saying politely.
Here's somebody said something very indiscreet.
Well, it was one of those things that is not acceptable.
It's one of the rules.
You can't do that.
And it was said.
And everybody just got up, the sophomores.
And it was directed at me.
And we hadn't rehearsed that.
And we were duck walking.
And the term was, do you?
get the duck walking faster.
Do you understand that?
Or do you want me to tell you in Spanish?
And it wasn't rehearsed.
Everybody got up in unison.
I said, you violated the rules of the game.
And we all left and went to one of the rooms.
And they screwed up.
That night, they couldn't touch us anymore.
And actually, we beat them at their game.
And it wasn't malicious.
It wasn't anything.
And this...
The young man that said it was from the valley.
And there was never any later retribution for young people.
Absolutely not.
I guess that was even the one I had to say.
That was the closest to a lot of popular questions.
Were there anything, being a minority, being a Mexican-American, was there any...
Anything ever directed at you?
No, not ever.
Never.
I'm not texting anything.
Now, the people that I've interviewed up through the war, through World War II, have said that there were nicknames that were not at all intended to be derisive.
Oh, absolutely.
But that they referred to some of the Jewish students as Jew boy.
And...
Those are Lebanese background.
We had our first sergeant, Paul Moenis, a Greek, and we all called him Greek.
We were proud of those kinds of things.
I had a nickname, which was Bully, but I grew up with that.
When my friends went up with me, to me, that was my only name because I never went by Raul.
People say, when they drop handles, what's your name?
I say Bully because that's what everybody ever called me.
Alright, was there ever, let's work on the minority bit of it, was there ever any, were you ever called Mexican or Latino?
Never.
Never a problem.
Was that true, as far as you know, pretty well campus-wide?
Absolutely.
But at that time, there were no blacks in Texas A&M, by law.
And I grew up in Laredo, and I didn't even know the minority.
I didn't find out maybe until I was 25 or 30.
I don't know.
But in Laredo, everybody spoke Spanish and everybody spoke English.
And it was a great community by that standard.
Now, you were bilingual.
Absolutely, yes.
And did that, at A&M, was that anything unusual?
Was that to your advantage or disadvantage?
Well, I got an A in a three-hour course, which is a great place to compete.
It was an advantage, not as far as being in the Corps or anything else.
It's always been an advantage to me.
As a student, it didn't make any difference.
Did you, was your freshman roommate, your fish hole lady, did that person become a special friend?
I went through several.
Oh, so.
Remember when you sat down that first day, the first sergeant told us, you know, look to your left, look to your right, because that guy's not going to be here at the end of this year.
We lost a lot of them.
I don't think my freshman roommates made it.
There's only about 11 or 12 of us.
Are there some special friends, though, from your class?
Christ.
Who are the most special?
Those are the friends that you have forever and for life.
Who are the most special ones?
Well, all the guys in my outfit were special.
Maybe one or two that had others, but we were so close because...
Most of us, and even those that did have something, you didn't know it.
And, you know, I can, well, Paul Moenis, he was also a CE major, civil engineering, and Wesley Hill, who's now the highway engineer, state of Texas, Mike Woodson, Tommy Lohman is my dear friend.
We still go skiing together.
Our wives are close.
Our wives are closer than we are, I think.
And they just tolerate us and invite us along wherever we go.
But some I don't see, and some have died.
But John Thomas, our class agent, was in our activity.
All right, describe for me some of the pranks, the good bull that you knew about, whether you were involved in or not.
Oh, I was involved in most of it.
All right, describe some of them.
The question of the drown outs are always special.
That's a lot of fun to drop a waste can of water on a sophomore.
When I was a sophomore, I've done it a million.
It's okay, the scar I have under my chin, diving out of bed and catching the backside of that freshman and I missed and I fell down and got a scar to prove it.
We, let me see, some of the real neat things that we did there.
Poor Buddy Majan.
Buddy, he's from the Valley.
And one time we had a fish, we had a fish beer bust.
Totally illegal, obviously.
But we went out, us freshmen, and we had a party.
And so we were out there in the, some open farm, ranch land, something like that.
Maybe out in the pits, I don't know.
And we were out there.
drinking beer and joined fellowship and the poor armadillo came through the area and it was night and that's when armadillos come out.
And so we, of course it was a bunch of freshmen trying to catch an armadillo and we finally caught him.
And we didn't hurt him, we just caught him.
And I said, well now we got him.
What are we going to do?
Somebody said, let's put him in Buddy Major's bed.
And so this armadillo was half scared to death.
And he might, you know, he was trying to act possum.
I think he was half possum.
So when we got back to the dorm, we were probably a little rowdy.
And the sophomores always need a good reason to get after you.
But that armadillo ended up in Buddy Major's bed.
And Bobby Muller, he was
He frogged in, so it was already our second semester.
Bobby Mueller, Frog Mueller, was one of Major's favorites because Bobby was a frog.
And as a matter of fact, he called him into his room, and he was sitting there fussing for something.
And he was in the process of getting into bed.
And I mean, he came out of that bed like a rocket.
You know, Joe Fenton.
Joe was Buddy's roommate, and Joe witnessed that.
That was so funny.
I could just, and Joe tells it even better.
I mean, it's just hilarious.
And Bobby was the one that put it in there.
And Buddy didn't know that, but he just, you know, he was getting him in there for some kind of training.
And, you know, we would always find.
Now, what was the retribution for that?
Oh, I'm sure we paid the price.
Now, that's the kind of good story that I very much want in here.
Do you remember any others?
No, that one's special.
Let me think here.
Did you all ever put any or know of any explosives that were put in someone's room?
Those were dangerous.
I hear there's some people that might have done that.
I've never had the pleasure of doing that.
No Babel bombs?
Babel bomb.
Yeah, there was, you know, you really had to, they really...
